This may not be a concrete proof but atleast having some idea is better than nothing. I could not find any good explanation out there, so please comment here if you have found a better resource :)


You might have already read the approach - 
1. initialise left and right pointers to 0 and size-1 respectively
2. find character to the left of right pointer which is equal to character at l and modify the string. If not found return -1 (handle odd length string case as well)

Why does this work? Why is it enough replace just 1 character (either to the left or right), could there be a better solution by replacing both characters ?

Think about this - No matter what you do, in order to align 2 characters in the given string, it would taken a min of swaps depending on the following 2 values - pos(right), pos(left) .i.e. in the end you will end up making these many swaps for sure for these 2 characters.

Now, you can notice that in our method we are exaclty doing this - making a minimum number of swaps. .i.e. moving one of the left or the right character by this minimum number of swaps.

```
class Solution {
    public int minMovesToMakePalindrome(String s) {

        int count = 0;
        int l = 0;
        int r = s.length()-1;

        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(s);

        int skip = 0;

        while(l<r){

            char leftChar = sb.charAt(l); 
            char rightChar = sb.charAt(r);
            int temp = r; 

            while(l < temp &&  leftChar != sb.charAt(temp)){
                temp--;
            }

            if(l == temp){
                if(s.length()%2 == 0){
                    return -1;
                } else {
                    if(skip == 1) return -1;
                    skip = 1;
                    count = count + s.length()/2 - l;
                    l = l + 1;
                }
                continue;
            }

            count = count + r - temp;

            sb.deleteCharAt(temp);
            sb.insert(r, leftChar);


            r--;
            l++;

        }



        return count;

    }
}
```

