solutions.content:
The idea is to consider two pointers, from left end and right end, to the middle.
Whenever there is a pair of the same letters, swap the right one towards the right end till it finds the correct position.
A special condition is that there might be a single letter on the left, which does not find its counterpart on the right. In this case, this letter should be moved to the middle.

One might wonder why we need to operate on the right one, but not the left one. It is equivalent to operate on the left one, and might result in a different result string though.

Time complexity `O(N^2)`
```
    int minMovesToMakePalindrome(string s) {
        int n = s.size(), res = 0, i = 0;
        while(i < n / 2)
        {
            int l = i, r = n - l - 1;
            while(l < r)
            {
                if (s[l] == s[r])
                    break;
                --r;
            }
            if (l == r)
            {
				// There is a single letter which should go to the middle.
                swap(s[l], s[l + 1]);
                ++res;
            }
            else
            {
				// Move the letter to the right till its correct position.
                for (int j = r; j < n - l - 1; ++j)
                {
                    swap(s[j], s[j + 1]);
                    ++res;
                }
                ++i;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
```

