# Intuition
Greedy approach -> 
    At each instance we can do following things: 
    1. keep left most character as-it-is, and make some moves to move other equivalent character to right. 
    2. keep right most character as-it-is, and make some moves to move other equivalent character to left. 
    Choose greedy solution which would needs to minimum moves to make left-most and right-most characters same. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

For example : 
consider - 
l--e--t--e--l--t
0-1--2-3--4-5 (indexes)
 to make left and right chars same, we have following 2 options
1. move l (at index 4) to 5th index - with move count 1
2. move t (at index 2) to 0th index - with move count 2 ( we needed 2 swaps).

From above 2 possibilities , we can chose first one (as it has lower moves) & repeat same for subproblem subproblem 
**e t e t**

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N^2)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minMovesToMakePalindrome(String str) {
        char[] s = str.toCharArray();
        return minMovesToMakePalindrome(s,0, s.length-1);
    }

    int minMovesToMakePalindrome(char[] s, int left, int right){

        while(left < right && s[left]==s[right]){
            left++;
            right--;
        }

        if(left>=right) return 0;

        int l = left+1;
        while(l < right && s[l]!=s[right]) l++;

        int r = right-1;
        while(left < r && s[r]!=s[left]) r--;

        int leftMoves = l-left;
        int rightMoves = right-r;  

        int currentMoves = 0; 

