solutions.content:
My idea:

The brute force solution is to find the all possible edge subsets `s1` from `dst` to `src1`
and all possible edge subsets `s2` from `dst` to `src2`, then merge the two subsets ...

But we cant just hope this solution passed. To reduce the high time complexity problem,
we can use dynamic programming.

For dynamic programming, we may want to cache the information of edges.
In this problem, each edges has 4 states:

* unused
* used in path `src1 -> dst`
* used in path `src2 -> dst`
* shared in path `src1 -> dst` and path `src2 -> dst`

Lets begin from the easy case. let `e[i]` denote the `i`-th edge, `f(e[i][0], e[i][1], state)` denote the
global minimum weigh for edge `e[i][0] -> e[i][1]` with state `state`. Then, if

* `state == unused, f(e[i][0], e[i][1], state) = -1` means unreachable
* `state == both_used`, `f(e[i][0], e[i][1], state)` equals `min_weight_e[i][1]_to_dst + min_weigh_src1&src2_to_e[i][0]`

Whats `min_weigh_src1&src2_to_e[i][0]`? It looks complex. Lets suppose the `e[i]` is the first shared edge, then

`min_weigh_src1&src2_to_e[i][0] = min_path(src1, e[i][0]) + min_path(src2, e[i][1])`.

Whats `min_weight_e[i][1]_to_dst`? If `e[i]` is the first shared edge, then all subsequent edges
should be also shared. then

`min_weight_e[i][1]_to_dst = min_path(e[i][1], dst)`

ok, we can interupt our dp solution. The global min weights is the sum

`min_path(e[i][1], dst) + min_path(src1, e[i][0]) + min_path(src2, e[i][0])` for the first shared edge
`e[i]` that is `e[i][0] -> e[i][1]`.

We dont know which one is the first. But we can try each edge as if it is the first edge,
if it isnt, the result dont effect the final result as it isnt the min one.
we can use dijkstra algorithm to find the min path.

In my code, I search the start node of the shared edges for simplify the logic.
The dijkstra algorithm is optimized for this problem.

Finally, Rust code

```rust
type Graph = Vec<Vec<(usize, i32)>>;

impl Solution {
    pub fn minimum_weight(n: i32, edges: Vec<Vec<i32>>, src1: i32, src2: i32, dest: i32) -> i64 {
        let n = n as usize;

        let (graph, rev_graph) = Solution::preprocess(n, &edges);

        let from_src1 = Solution::dijkstra(src1 as usize, n, &graph);
        let from_src2 = Solution::dijkstra(src2 as usize, n, &graph);
        let to_dest = Solution::dijkstra(dest as usize, n, &rev_graph);

        (0..n)
            .filter(|&i| from_src1[i] != -1 && from_src2[i] != -1 && to_dest[i] != -1)
            .map(|i| from_src1[i] + from_src2[i] + to_dest[i])
            .min()
            .unwrap_or(-1)
    }

    fn preprocess(n: usize, edges: &Vec<Vec<i32>>) -> (Graph, Graph) {
        let mut graph = vec![vec![]; n];
        let mut rev_graph = vec![vec![]; n];
        for e in edges {
            let e0 = e[0] as usize;
            let e1 = e[1] as usize;

            graph[e0].push((e1, e[2]));
            rev_graph[e1].push((e0, e[2]));
        }
        (graph, rev_graph)
    }

    fn dijkstra(src: usize, n: usize, graph: &Graph) -> Vec<i64> {
        let mut dist = vec![-1; n];
        let mut to_visit = std::collections::BinaryHeap::new();

        to_visit.push(MinPath { node: src, dist: 0 });

        while let Some(MinPath { node, dist: mydist }) = to_visit.pop() {
            if dist[node] != -1 {
                continue;
            }
            dist[node] = mydist;
            for &(adj, w) in &graph[node] {
                if dist[adj] == -1 {
                    to_visit.push(MinPath {
                        node: adj,
                        dist: dist[node] + w as i64,
                    });
                }
            }
        }

        dist
    }
}

#[derive(Eq, Ord)]
struct MinPath {
    node: usize,
    dist: i64,
}

impl PartialEq for MinPath {
    fn eq(&self, other: &Self) -> bool {
        self.dist == other.dist
    }
}

impl PartialOrd for MinPath {
    fn partial_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Option<std::cmp::Ordering> {
        other.dist.partial_cmp(&self.dist)
    }
}
