    private void shortestPath(int src, long[] srcTo, ArrayList<int[]>[] graph) {
        PriorityQueue<long[]> heap = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> (a[1] == b[1] ? 0 : (a[1] < b[1] ? -1 : 1)));
        for (int[] next : graph[src]) {
            heap.offer(new long[] {next[0], next[1]});
        }

        srcTo[src] = 0;

        while (!heap.isEmpty()) {
            long[] node = heap.poll();
            long to = node[0], dist = node[1];
            if (srcTo[(int) to] != -1 && srcTo[(int) to] <= dist) continue;
            srcTo[(int) to] = dist;
            for (int[] next : graph[(int) to]) {
                heap.offer(new long[] {next[0], dist + next[1]});
            }
        }
    }
}
```

solutions.content:
Run Dijkstra algorithm 3 times:
- from each of the two sources (on original graph)
- from destination (on graph with inverted edges)
- take the minimum of the sum of distances to the 3 points across all nodes

The Dijkstra implementation is left as an exercise to the reader :-)

```
public long minimumWeight(int n, int[][] edges, int src1, int src2, int dest) {
	// graph and inverted graph
	List<long[]>[] g= new ArrayList[n], ig= new ArrayList[n];
	for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
		g[i]= new ArrayList<>();
		ig[i]= new ArrayList<>();
	}
	for(int[] e:edges){
		int u= e[0], v= e[1], w= e[2];
		g[u].add(new long[]{v, w});
		ig[v].add(new long[]{u, w});
	}
	long[] dist1= dijkstraPQ(n, g, src1);
	long[] dist2= dijkstraPQ(n, g, src2);
	long[] dist3= dijkstraPQ(n, ig, dest);
	long ans= INF;
	for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
		ans= Math.min(ans, dist1[i]+dist2[i]+dist3[i]);
	}
	return ans>=INF ? -1 : ans;
}

